FAIR PRINCIPAL COMPONENT ANALYSIS,0.06030150753768844,"In the fair PCA setting, we are also given a discrete sensitive attribute A ‚ààA, where A may represent
features such as race, gender or education. We consider binary attribute A and let A = {0, 1}. A
straightforward idea to deÔ¨Åne fairness is to require the (strict) balance of a certain objective between
the two groups. For example, this is the strategy in Hardt et al. (2016a) for developing fair supervised
learning algorithms. A natural objective to balance in the PCA context is the reconstruction error.
DeÔ¨Ånition 2.1 (Fair projection). Let Q be an arbitrary distribution of (X, A). A projection matrix
V ‚ààRd√ók is fair relative to Q if the conditional expected reconstruction error is equal between
subgroups, i.e., EQ[‚Ñì(V, X)|A = a] = EQ[‚Ñì(V, X)|A = a‚Ä≤] for any (a, a‚Ä≤) ‚ààA √ó A."
FAIR PRINCIPAL COMPONENT ANALYSIS,0.06281407035175879,"Unfortunately, DeÔ¨Ånition 2.1 is too stringent: for a general probability distribution Q, it is possible
that there exists no fair projection matrix V .
Proposition 2.2 (Impossibility result). For any distribution Q on X √óA, there exists a fair projection
matrix V ‚ààRd√ók relative to Q if and only if rank(EQ[XX‚ä§|A = 0] ‚àíEQ[XX‚ä§|A = 1]) ‚â§k."
FAIR PRINCIPAL COMPONENT ANALYSIS,0.06532663316582915,"One way to circumvent the impossibility result is to relax the requirement of strict balance to ap-
proximate balance. In other words, an inequality constraint of the following form is imposed:
|EQ[‚Ñì(V, X)|A = a] ‚àíEQ[‚Ñì(V, X)|A = a‚Ä≤]| ‚â§œµ
