RETRACTIONS,0.24874371859296482,"Another important instrument required by the framework in Li et al. (2021) is a retraction of the
Stiefel manifold M. At each iteration, the point U ‚àíŒ≥‚àÜobtained by moving from the current
iterate U in the opposite direction of the Riemannian gradient ‚àÜmay not lie on the manifold in
general, where Œ≥ > 0 is the stepsize. In Riemannian optimization, this is circumvented by the
concept of retraction. Given a point U ‚ààM on the manifold, the Riemannian gradient ‚àÜ‚àà
TUM (which must lie in the tangent space TUM) and a stepsize Œ≥, the retraction map Rtr deÔ¨Ånes a
point RtrU(‚àíŒ≥‚àÜ) which is guaranteed to lie on the manifold M. Roughly speaking, the retraction
RtrU( ¬∑ ) approximates the geodesic curve through U along the input tangential direction. For a
formal deÔ¨Ånition of retractions, we refer the readers to (Absil et al., 2007, Section 4.1). In this
paper, we focus on the following two commonly used retractions for Stiefel manifolds. The Ô¨Årst one
is the QR decomposition-based retraction using the Q-factor qf( ¬∑ ) in the QR decomposition:"
